		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 12:34 PM2000 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=3&mid=96656576029157&num=6&page=&post=1&replyto=96661649419234"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=96661649419234></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.14]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Anonymous&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Being a somewhat mid-level Monk, I have learned through trial and error what is the best stat to be improved at creation and it is &lt;U&gt;strenght&lt;/U&gt;. The simple reason for this is a little skill called Feign Death.<br><br>Godly skill this Feign Death; I've heard rumors of Verant going to nerf it into some sort of "evade" skill, and if they do, I'm dropping my Monk altoghether. The point I'm trying to make is that AGI raises your AC, but in later level (past 17), your AC doesn't matter because you can always Feign Death if things go haywire while soloing. As for groups, clerics and druids will supply the AC buffs for you; especially in HIGH level groups, when you're packing a ten pound 2HB weapon with the best damage-delay ratio around, losing about 50points of AC just because of the sheer weight of it all. Besides, the Monk class has been made to be the best meelee damage dealer in the game, so groups in the know will recruit the strongest monk around (so all the creatures get pulled on to him, heh heh).<br><br>A word about allocating your beginning SKILL points now. Basicly, I see only 4 disciplines that require more then one point put into it: Mend, Feign Death, Instill Doubt and Flying Kick.<br><br>Any other combat skill only requires the one first point, (except for when you're starting a total newbie character, and you need all the help you can get). Trade skills MIGHT be a good idea, depending on how you play your character (however, let me tell you that I sold my cured silk Gi in North Freeport for 20PP, so I know that tailoring is profitable). You should put points into mend until you feel comfortable with the skill and start saving for Feign Death; the godly skill. Instill Doubt is an iffy: I only suggest putting points into it because I heard that it was a hard skill to build up. You'll learn Flying Kick at level 30, and you'll want to bring it up to speed ASAP, hence the saving of skill points; however, remember to save one skill point to learn the basics of Riposte afterwards!<br><br><br>For those who want to learn a trade, please understand that cured silk sells for A LOT more then the usual 2PP per AC that everyone tells you, and I commonly put an arbitrary price ranging from 10 to 20PP on every piece of cured silk. Therefore, the three trades that a Monk should learn would be Brewing, Blacksmithing and Tailoring.<br><br>To quickly raise skill points in Brewing, go from Bog Juice, Short Beer, Fish Wine, (to something else, I forget, I believe Ale. Just check one of the million guides on brewing, okay?) then to Heady Kiolas. Blacksmithings raises easy... if you live in Freeport (D'OH, says the agnostic Queynos Monk writting this thing). Simply put, nobody wants the rusty swords given up in those over-camped DF orc camps, so just ask nicely (or sneak nicely) and loot all the rusted stuff you can find, and sharpen until 21. On a personal note, I never learned blacksmithing, and I've had ALL the trouble in the world in finding someone who would make me metal studs and steel borings. Tailoring raises easy when you figure out that the cost of a ruined pelt from a merchant + the price of a pattern is less then the resale value of patchwork armor to the merchant. Oh yeah, and the new "spider threads" (two spiderling silks put together) should be a cool new way to raise skill from what was once a useless dropped item.<br><br>On another personal note, I've tried out Pottery for the sheer fun of it, and realised that even WITHOUT any skill points, this is the fastest rising trade skill in the game. Bought for about 10 small jars, and raised my skill to 8, just like that. I'm moving from small, to medium to large clay jars without knowing what I'll do next, and I already have my skill in the lower forties for less then 2plats.<br><br><br>In closing, I seriously regret the fact that I grew up in Queynos: I bought a Bamboo Bo Stick for 100PP, a drolvags mantle for the same price, got a lumberjacks cap for 6DF belts and sold five peices of cured silk for 90PP (and the Gi wasn't part of the deal)... only in Freeport.<br><br><br>Neige Thirteen<br>Fighting Snowman of Veeshan Server<br>Supreme Fearless Leader of the Eastern Assassins<br>www.maxpages.com/eassassins<br>"I got's mo' funk then your average monk, fruitbootie!"<br><br>PS: and next time I grace this board, a guide on moving up equipment-wise, FOR MONKS!</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >2 Replies</td></tr></table><table width="100%"><tr><td class=mhback>&nbsp;</td><td class=mhback >Thread Subject</a></td><td class=mhback>Started by</a></td><td class=mhback>Replies</a></td><td class=mhback>Last Post</a></td><td class=mhback>Rating</a></td></tr><tr class=mlr>
